.TH HSH 1 "May 2026" "Simple Shell 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hsh \- a simple UNIX command line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ./hsh
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a minimal UNIX command line interpreter written in C. It reads commands
from standard input, parses them, and executes them in a child process using
.BR execve (2).
It replicates the most essential features of
.BR sh (1).
.PP
When invoked without arguments,
.B hsh
runs in interactive mode: it prints the prompt
.B "$ " ,
waits for a command, executes it, and repeats until end-of-file
.RB ( Ctrl+D )
or the
.B exit
built-in is entered.
.PP
When standard input is not a terminal,
.B hsh
runs in non-interactive mode: it reads commands from the input stream,
executes them silently, and exits when input is exhausted.
.SH INVOCATION
Commands are read one line at a time. Each line is split into tokens
delimited by whitespace. The first token is the command; the remaining
tokens are passed as arguments. Empty lines and lines containing only
whitespace are ignored. A maximum of 64 tokens per line is supported
(63 arguments plus the command itself).
.SH COMMAND EXECUTION
If the command name contains a slash, it is treated as a path and executed
directly.
.PP
Otherwise,
.B hsh
searches for the executable in each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable, in order. The first matching executable file is run.
If no match is found, an error is printed and
.BR fork (2)
is not called.
.PP
A new process is created with
.BR fork (2),
and the command is executed in the child with
.BR execve (2).
The parent waits for the child to terminate before printing the prompt again.
.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS
.TP
.B exit
Exits the shell with the exit status of the last executed command.
Any arguments are silently ignored.
.TP
.B env
Prints the current environment, one variable per line, in the form
.IR VARIABLE=value .
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.B hsh
inherits the environment from its parent process. The following variable
affects its behavior:
.TP
.B PATH
A colon-separated list of directories searched for executable commands.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B hsh
returns the exit status of the last executed command. If a command is not
found, the exit status is
.BR 127 .
On
.B exit
or end-of-file, the shell returns the exit status of the most recently
executed command.
.SH ERRORS
If a command cannot be found,
.B hsh
prints a message of the form:
.PP
.RS
./hsh: 1: command: not found
.RE
.PP
to standard error and continues to the next prompt.
.SH EXAMPLES
Interactive use:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ ./hsh
$ /bin/ls
AUTHORS README.md hsh
$ ls
AUTHORS README.md hsh
$ env
PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin
HOME=/home/user
$ exit
$
.fi
.RE
.PP
Non-interactive use:
.PP
.RS
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
AUTHORS README.md hsh
.fi
.RE
.SH LIMITATIONS
.IP \(bu 2
A maximum of 63 arguments per command (fixed-size token array).
.IP \(bu 2
The
.B exit
built-in does not accept an exit code argument; it always exits with the
status of the last executed command.
.IP \(bu 2
No support for pipes
.RB ( | ),
redirections
.RB ( > ", " < ),
or semicolons
.RB ( ; ).
.IP \(bu 2
No support for variable expansion or quoting.
.IP \(bu 2
No support for command history or line editing.
.IP \(bu 2
No support for job control or background execution
.RB ( & ).
.IP \(bu 2
Aliases, functions, and shell scripts are not supported.
.SH BUGS
This shell intentionally implements only a small subset of POSIX sh
behavior. See the
.B LIMITATIONS
section above for unsupported features. Report any unexpected behavior
to the authors listed in the
.B AUTHORS
file.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR sh (1),
.BR bash (1),
.BR execve (2),
.BR fork (2),
.BR wait (2),
.BR getline (3),
.BR environ (7)
